  "why": "The paper provides partial diagnostic insight into discovered failures: it characterizes failure patterns across ASR systems (per‑ASR failure counts, comparisons of ASR reliabilities) and analyzes false positives by categorizing their causes (TTS issues, preprocessing shortcomings, ambiguous audio). However, it does not trace failures to underlying model vulnerabilities such as corrupted/biased training data, spurious features, or internal model behavior (no analysis of model internals, activations, or training data causes). Thus the paper offers characterization of failure properties but not explanatory linkage to root causes in the models themselves.",
  "evidence": "Section III.D (Results) — per‑ASR failure concentration: \"From this perspective, Wit can be considered as the worst ASR among the 4 since it has the highest number of failed test cases. Wav2Letter++ can be considered as the best ASR since it has the lowest number of failed test cases.\" (Section III.D, RQ1 results, pp. 5–6). \n\nSection IV.B (Analysis of False Positive Failed Test Case from Manual Verification) — characterization of failure causes: \"From 33,618 failed test cases, we manually verified a statistically representative sample of size 395 and found 12 of them to be false positives. We analyze these false positives and observed that they can be categorized into 4 different cases: (1) Human deems the audio to be the same as the transcribed text, but different from the original text. ... (2) Human deems the audio to be different from both transcribed and input text. ... (3) Cases highlighting limitations of our Text Preprocessing step. ... (4) Audio is ambiguous; It can match both texts.\" (Section IV.B, p. 9). \n\nSection IV.A (Examples) — concrete failure examples illustrating error patterns (characterization, not root‑cause analysis): \"DeepSpeech mistakenly transcribed 'consulted' to 'controlled'. DeepSpeech2 mistakenly transcribed 'and the mess' to 'in the met'. Wav2letter++ mistakenly transcribed 'transport' to 'trains'. Wit mistakenly transcribed 'an old objective' to 'another project'.\" (Section IV.A, pp. 8–9). \n\nAbsence of deeper root‑cause linkage: the paper presents counts, examples, and false‑positive categories but contains no analysis linking failures to model internals, training data bias, or spurious feature reliance (no sections analyzing activations, training data, or techniques such as adversarial feature inspection). (Entire paper: diagnostic analysis is limited to the above characterizations; see Sections III and IV)."
